but something's wrong.

231
00:12:26,879 --> 00:12:31,807
He's out till all hours, always soused,  
and doesn't want word on with me."

232
00:12:31,807 --> 00:12:34,065
Sounds right. 
Who signed it?

233
00:12:34,065 --> 00:12:36,563
- "Should I Scream?" 
- That ain't helpful.

234
00:12:36,563 --> 00:12:40,820
Return address on the envelope:  
Mrs. Arthur Pool, Gildar Street.

235
00:12:40,820 --> 00:12:42,529
Gildar's in Fox Chase.

236
00:12:42,529 --> 00:12:45,536
Train station out there... 
Lawndale.

237
00:12:45,536 --> 00:12:49,363
So maybe this Arthur lures  
our girl out to his local train stop...

238
00:12:49,363 --> 00:12:53,300
Just in time to meet 
the 10:00 p.m. express.

239
00:12:57,479 --> 00:12:59,367
Arthur Pool was my father.

240
00:12:59,367 --> 00:13:01,669
He just passed away.

241
00:13:01,669 --> 00:13:03,414
I'm sorry.

242
00:13:03,414 --> 00:13:05,149
We're sitting shave for him.

243
00:13:05,149 --> 00:13:07,215
We're here about a homicide.

244
00:13:07,215 --> 00:13:09,170
Your dad knew our victim.

245
00:13:09,170 --> 00:13:12,369
Well, he obviously can't help you.

246
00:13:12,369 --> 00:13:14,304
Her name was Lorena Kinney.

247
00:13:14,304 --> 00:13:17,027
Your mom wrote to her 
for advice, back in '45.

248
00:13:17,027 --> 00:13:19,016
Which ticked your dad off pretty good.

249
00:13:19,016 --> 00:13:21,067
My dad did not kill Lo.

250
00:13:21,067 --> 00:13:23,289
- So you knew her? 
- I met her in this house.

251
00:13:23,289 --> 00:13:27,067
Really? Cause we heard she and your dad  
went toe-to-toe in the newsroom.

252
00:13:27,067 --> 00:13:30,570
She came here the next day, 
and that's when she met Noah.

253
00:13:30,570 --> 00:13:32,467
- Who's that? 
- My uncle.

254
00:13:32,467 --> 00:13:34,210
He live with you?

255
00:13:34,783 --> 00:13:36,785
Lucky for me.

256
00:13:36,785 --> 00:13:38,587
He was my real father figure.

257
00:13:38,587 --> 00:13:42,084
Cause your dad came home 
from the war in rough shape? / Right.

258
00:13:42,084 --> 00:13:44,639
Noah taught me how to be a kid,

259
00:13:44,639 --> 00:13:50,016
shoot marbles, ask out a girl,  
drive. / Nice.

260
00:13:50,016 --> 00:13:53,614
What was Lo's relationship with Noah?

261
00:13:54,263 --> 00:13:58,262
Love... at first sight.

262
00:14:00,373 --> 00:14:03,184
I'm here to apologize,  
I guess.

263
00:14:03,184 --> 00:14:06,255
A good reporter's got to hear 
both sides of a story.

264
00:14:06,255 --> 00:14:07,738
You willing to tell it?

265
00:14:07,738 --> 00:14:12,374
Look, uh... I love my wife,

266
00:14:12,374 --> 00:14:16,627
but the things I seen and... 
and done in this war...

267
00:14:16,627 --> 00:14:19,115
those memories got to stay 
out of this house.

268
00:14:19,115 --> 00:14:23,835
Daddy, me and Uncle Noah 
saw Pinocchio and get marbles!

269
00:14:23,835 --> 00:14:25,746
That's nice, David.

270
00:14:25,746 --> 00:14:29,218
Now, don't go interrupting  
the grownups, you hear?

271
00:14:31,864 --> 00:14:36,552
Oh, we play later, David. 
What do you say?

272
00:14:38,008 --> 00:14:41,181
It'll be our secret.

273
00:14:41,181 --> 00:14:43,436
Noah, this is, uh, Lo Kinney,

274
00:14:43,436 --> 00:14:45,934
the advice lady  
I was moaning about.

275
00:14:45,934 --> 00:14:48,257
- Pleased to meet you. 
- Likewise.

276
00:14:48,257 --> 00:14:50,877
I am fan of your column, 
"Dear Lo."

277
00:14:50,877 --> 00:14:53,440
- Now, that's bunk. 
- No, it's true.

278
00:14:53,440 --> 00:14:58,374
A month ago, a woman asks 
what type of curtains you use,

279
00:14:58,374 --> 00:15:01,539
and you tell her "none, so you 
can see the sky."

280
00:15:01,539 --> 00:15:03,303
Quite a memory you got...

281
00:15:03,303 --> 00:15:05,920
especially since I was shoveling it  
pretty hard, quite frankly.

282
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:09,600
Oh, you strike me as the type  
of woman to whom the truth...

283
00:15:09,600 --> 00:15:11,924
is everything.

284
00:15:13,393 --> 00:15:15,238
Haven't lived long in Philadelphia?

285
00:15:15,238 --> 00:15:17,491
Uh, Noah's from, uh Holland.

286
00:15:17,491 --> 00:15:19,328
- Swal... 
- Swalmen.

287
00:15:19,328 --> 00:15:21,261
And she doesn't care to hear about me.

288
00:15:21,261 --> 00:15:23,792
Sure. Sure, I do.

289
00:15:24,986 --> 00:15:26,894
I mean... that... that's what I do.

290
00:15:26,894 --> 00:15:29,491
I listen to people.

291
00:15:29,491 --> 00:15:33,318
Uh, turns out,  
uh, Noah and I are third cousins.

292
00:15:33,318 --> 00:15:36,599
He made it out of Europe 
right when it was getting real bad.

293
00:15:36,599 --> 00:15:38,104
How'd you swing that?

294
00:15:38,104 --> 00:15:41,501
During the war, um, things are confusing.

295
00:15:41,501 --> 00:15:45,355
Um, I escaped and made it to Switzerland.

296
00:15:45,355 --> 00:15:48,892
He got out of that camp: 
Auschwitz.

297
00:15:48,892 --> 00:15:51,053
Is that right?

298
00:15:51,053 --> 00:15:54,086
- I hear it was horrible. 
- Yes.

299
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:57,528
Now, that's a story people should hear.

300
00:15:57,528 --> 00:16:00,331
What if I tell you other stories?

301
00:16:00,331 --> 00:16:04,331
What if you tell me all your stories?

302
00:16:04,331 --> 00:16:07,159
Maybe I will.

303
00:16:09,266 --> 00:16:11,459
So Lo was your uncle's girl.

304
00:16:11,459 --> 00:16:14,021
Um, "lady friend" was his term.

305
00:16:14,021 --> 00:16:16,617
So much for Helen's old maid theory.

306
00:16:16,617 --> 00:16:18,259
Is Noah here now?

307
00:16:18,259 --> 00:16:21,644
He was, but this time of day,  
he's home...

308
00:16:21,644 --> 00:16:24,289
painting up a storm.

309
00:16:30,957 --> 00:16:32,423
Noah Pool?

310
00:16:33,343 --> 00:16:36,121
Detectives Miller and Vera.

311
00:16:36,121 --> 00:16:40,407
Come on in. 
I don't get many visitors here.

312
00:16:40,407 --> 00:16:43,766
- Dark stuff. 
- Maybe that's why no visitors.

313
00:16:43,766 --> 00:16:46,053
Mr. Pool, we're here about Lorena Kinney.

314
00:16:46,053 --> 00:16:49,396
Yeah, David said 
you were looking into her death.

315
00:16:49,396 --> 00:16:51,333
You think it wasn't an accident?

316
00:16:51,333 --> 00:16:52,941
Maybe not.

317
00:16:52,941 --> 00:16:54,870
That's awful.

318
00:16:54,870 --> 00:16:57,442
We heard you two were an item.

319
00:16:57,835 --> 00:16:59,836
From the moment we met.

320
00:16:59,836 --> 00:17:02,185
There's no mention of you in 
the police report when she died.

321
00:17:02,185 --> 00:17:04,905
- I didn't come forward. 
- That's kind of strange.

322
00:17:04,905 --> 00:17:07,742
I will illegal. 
I wasn't even supposed to exist.

323
00:17:07,742 --> 00:17:09,800
And you were worried the cops 
were going to send you back?

324
00:17:09,800 --> 00:17:13,624
They would have. 
I had nothing to go back to.

325
00:17:13,624 --> 00:17:16,894
Family, friends... all dead.

326
00:17:16,894 --> 00:17:19,607
Right before her death,  
Lo received a note saying,

327
00:17:19,607 --> 00:17:23,528
"This will not stand," 
and setting up a meet at the train station.

328
00:17:23,528 --> 00:17:25,075
Where she was killed.

329
00:17:25,075 --> 00:17:26,511
You didn't write it, did you?

330
00:17:26,511 --> 00:17:33,250
No. Lo was my second chance 
after so much darkness.

331
00:17:33,250 --> 00:17:38,445
I came here to start over, 
and there she was. Light.

332
00:17:39,200 --> 00:17:43,493
When she died, though, 
that... light went out for good.

333
00:17:43,493 --> 00:17:48,243
Can you think of anyone who 
could have written that to her?

334
00:17:48,243 --> 00:17:52,764
Yes. 
One person.

335
00:17:58,001 --> 00:18:00,381
- Cotton candy. 
- Oh.

336
00:18:00,381 --> 00:18:02,595
It's pretty good, huh?

337
00:18:02,595 --> 00:18:04,658
That is so sweet.

338
00:18:04,658 --> 00:18:08,263
The war's almost over. 
We're starting to get sugar again.

339
00:18:08,263 --> 00:18:12,142
It's nice, this place. 
Seeing the sky.

340
00:18:12,142 --> 00:18:15,339
For a long time, I see it 
only through barbed wire.

341
00:18:15,339 --> 00:18:17,634
Must've felt like the world was ending.

342
00:18:17,634 --> 00:18:20,747
Huh. It was ending.

343
00:18:20,747 --> 00:18:23,793
- Will you ever go back to Holland? 
- Why would I?

344
00:18:23,793 --> 00:18:26,078
Family, your childhood home.

345
00:18:26,078 --> 00:18:30,243
No, there's nothing there. 
Not even me.

346
00:18:30,243 --> 00:18:34,500
Whoever I thought I was, 
I left that person behind.

347
00:18:34,500 --> 00:18:37,211
I think I know the feeling.

348
00:18:40,011 --> 00:18:42,968
Noah. 
You're here now.

349
00:18:42,968 --> 00:18:46,220
When they came for us...

350
00:18:46,220 --> 00:18:48,637
they put us on trains.

351
00:18:48,637 --> 00:18:52,727
That is the last time 
I saw my mother, my sisters...

352
00:18:52,727 --> 00:18:55,312
and I got separated from  
my father at the camp.

353
00:18:55,312 --> 00:18:57,169
I never saw them again.

354
00:18:57,169 --> 00:18:59,468
- How long were you there? 
- Three years.

355
00:18:59,468 --> 00:19:03,503
I lived because I could paint.

356
00:19:03,503 --> 00:19:05,461
The guards liked that.

357
00:19:05,461 --> 00:19:07,881
What'd they like about it?

358
00:19:07,881 --> 00:19:10,603
I painted their portraits.

359
00:19:11,353 --> 00:19:15,375
For hours... 
I'd look at their faces...

360
00:19:15,375 --> 00:19:19,086
these men who kill my family...

361
00:19:19,086 --> 00:19:23,781
- and painted them. 
- Oh, Noah.

362
00:19:24,107 --> 00:19:28,775
It's nice to see the sky.

363
00:19:32,069 --> 00:19:34,529
What do you say we take a picture?

364
00:19:34,529 --> 00:19:37,101
What? 
Uh, wait..

365
00:19:37,101 --> 00:19:41,441
To remember today, forever. 
Come on...

366
00:19:58,357 --> 00:20:02,030
You're, uh... 
You're hard to pin down.

367
00:20:02,030 --> 00:20:04,428
What?

368
00:20:04,428 --> 00:20:06,755
You are like a wild bird.

369
00:20:06,755 --> 00:20:10,023
You want to flit. Fly.

370
00:20:10,023 --> 00:20:13,585
- I'm just an everyday gal. 
- No.

371
00:20:13,585 --> 00:20:16,608
That's what's good.

372
00:20:25,527 --> 00:20:27,902
You're good.

373
00:20:28,781 --> 00:20:31,821
- What's going on here? 
- Birdie! Were you following me?

374
00:20:31,821 --> 00:20:34,979
You're just throwing 
it all away. Is that it?

375
00:20:34,979 --> 00:20:36,660
It's not what you think, Birdie.

376
00:20:36,660 --> 00:20:38,967
Well, the hell with you then, Lo!

377
00:20:38,967 --> 00:20:42,451
The hell with you!

378
00:20:43,667 --> 00:20:45,617
- I have to go to him. 
- No, Lo, wait.

379
00:20:45,617 --> 00:20:47,359
I'm sorry.

380
00:20:47,359 --> 00:20:49,849
I have to go.

381
00:20:53,145 --> 00:20:54,888
Lo and Birdie had some history?

382
00:20:54,888 --> 00:20:57,484
She always said they were 
just pals from work.

383
00:20:57,484 --> 00:20:59,932
What he told us, too.

384
00:21:00,405 --> 00:21:04,828
I don't know any "pals" that act like that.

385
00:21:10,459 --> 00:21:12,863
Firecracker like Lo wasn't dating material?

386
00:21:12,863 --> 00:21:14,985
- Isn't that what you said, Birdie? 
- Yes.

387
00:21:14,985 --> 00:21:17,682
So what's with you following her  
to Victory Park,

388
00:21:17,682 --> 00:21:19,274
throwing a jealous fit when  
you find her with Noah?

389
00:21:19,274 --> 00:21:21,265
That wasn't what it seemed.

390
00:21:21,265 --> 00:21:22,973
Seems like you were 
sick in love with her.

391
00:21:22,973 --> 00:21:26,568
- That's not what I was after. 
- Then what?

392
00:21:26,568 --> 00:21:30,203
I needed her help, right then.

393
00:21:30,203 --> 00:21:32,283
With?

394
00:21:34,842 --> 00:21:37,729
I had a story due.

395
00:21:37,729 --> 00:21:40,811
And Lo had been writing them for me.

396
00:21:40,811 --> 00:21:44,976
- Lo wrote your articles? 
- It started out, she just edited me.

397
00:21:44,976 --> 00:21:48,254
Down the line,  
I'd go to her under pressure.

398
00:21:48,254 --> 00:21:50,742
She could whip up a story in no time.

399
00:21:50,742 --> 00:21:52,878
And you couldn't?

400
00:21:54,210 --> 00:21:58,853
I was a five-cent reporter  
in a ten-cent job.

401
00:21:59,562 --> 00:22:01,436
And Lo was covering for you.

402
00:22:01,436 --> 00:22:04,288
I had a byline, no stories.

403
00:22:04,288 --> 00:22:08,252
- But Lo had a million stories. 
- But no byline.

404
00:22:08,252 --> 00:22:12,685
I'd promised McDuff a feature on a man  
who survived the worst in Europe,

405
00:22:12,685 --> 00:22:15,592
- was rebuilding his life here. 
- A story on Noah.

406
00:22:15,592 --> 00:22:18,834
Problem was, Lo was 
supposed to be reporting,

407
00:22:18,834 --> 00:22:23,290
not mooning around, falling in love.

408
00:22:24,023 --> 00:22:27,734
 ♪ You always hurt? ♪

409
00:22:27,734 --> 00:22:30,784
 ♪ The one you love... ♪

410
00:22:30,784 --> 00:22:33,111
You had no right acting  
the way you did in the park... no right!

411
00:22:33,111 --> 00:22:34,986
You promised me that  
front-page story this morning!

412
00:22:34,986 --> 00:22:36,998
McDuff has been breathing 
down my neck all day!

413
00:22:36,998 --> 00:22:39,222
Birdie, you've got a brain and ten fingers.

414
00:22:39,222 --> 00:22:40,667
And even if you only use  
two of them to type,

415
00:22:40,667 --> 00:22:42,290
nothing's stopping you 
from doing your own reporting.

416
00:22:42,290 --> 00:22:44,251
So you backing out 
of the story, is that it?

417
00:22:44,251 --> 00:22:48,485
No. I just... I... 
I need more time.

418
00:22:48,485 --> 00:22:50,562
You need more time cause 
you're falling for this fella.

419
00:22:50,562 --> 00:22:53,064
I certainly am not.

420
00:22:53,064 --> 00:22:56,966
Well, I hope you know what 
you're getting yourself into.

421
00:22:57,645 --> 00:22:59,656
What do you mean by that?

422
00:22:59,656 --> 00:23:01,936
Well, you're the one who said 
his story doesn't add up.

423
00:23:01,936 --> 00:23:04,458
Him escaping through 
Switzerland, for starters.

424
00:23:04,458 --> 00:23:05,967
People got out however they could.

425
00:23:05,967 --> 00:23:08,954
The Swiss borders were tight, especially  
for Jews... you told me that.

426
00:23:08,954 --> 00:23:10,952
And what about being in that camp?

427
00:23:10,952 --> 00:23:14,110
All the prisoners got tattoos on their arms. 
You said you were gonna check if he had one.

428
00:23:14,110 --> 00:23:17,169
- I never looked. 
- Why not?

429
00:23:20,036 --> 00:23:23,128
Look who's talking, buster.

430
00:23:23,450 --> 00:23:25,180
Back when you cared about this story,

431
00:23:25,180 --> 00:23:28,920
you asked me to track someone 
down from his hometown.

432
00:23:28,920 --> 00:23:33,011
Remember? 
Well, I did.

433
00:23:33,011 --> 00:23:36,764
Her name is Johanna Hoffman,  
from Swalmen, Holland.

434
00:23:36,764 --> 00:23:39,287
Birdie! I need that story, on the double!

435
00:23:39,287 --> 00:23:43,577
You want the truth about Noah? 
The real truth?

436
00:23:43,577 --> 00:23:46,517
Ask her.

437
00:23:51,981 --> 00:23:54,153
Did Lo ever follow up with this woman?

438
00:23:54,153 --> 00:23:56,317
Never said.

439
00:23:56,317 --> 00:24:01,197
But the kind of reporter she was,  
I can't imagine she didn't.

440
00:24:01,197 --> 00:24:04,326
And then she was dead.

441
00:24:08,957 --> 00:24:13,130
Found this mystery woman, 
Johanna Hoffman.

442
00:24:13,130 --> 00:24:15,474
- She still around? 
- Lives up in New York.

443
00:24:15,474 --> 00:24:18,720
And get this... 
relocated in July of '45.

444
00:24:18,720 --> 00:24:21,952
- About the same time Lo died. 
- Well, not about, exactly.

445
00:24:21,952 --> 00:24:24,454
Closed her bank account July 17th.

446
00:24:24,454 --> 00:24:26,643
Paper trail in Philly goes cold after that.

447
00:24:26,643 --> 00:24:30,759
So Johanna disappears and 
Lo winds up dead, same day.

448
00:24:30,759 --> 00:24:34,299
Lo must've gone to find her. 
Something went bad.

449
00:24:34,299 --> 00:24:37,649
Looks like someone's  
heading to New York. / Uh...

450
00:24:37,649 --> 00:24:41,669
There's a big poker game 
at my brother's tonight, so...

451
00:24:41,669 --> 00:24:44,573
It's Wednesday. 
Veronica's ballet class.

452
00:24:44,573 --> 00:24:47,718
Don't look at me; I'm planted.

453
00:24:47,718 --> 00:24:50,705
Guess that leaves me.

454
00:24:50,705 --> 00:24:54,059
I'm away, boss

455
00:24:56,774 --> 00:25:00,279
You're covering those 
phones like a champ, Will.

456
00:25:00,279 --> 00:25:06,929
Yeah. 61 years old, getting punished 
like a schoolboy. / Yeah.

457
00:25:06,929 --> 00:25:11,141
Yeah. Maybe time to go out.

458
00:25:11,675 --> 00:25:14,992
- Maybe. 
- No reason to keep it up.

459
00:25:14,992 --> 00:25:18,126
Deal with crummy people 
who lie to you all day.

460
00:25:18,126 --> 00:25:19,762
Dog's life.

461
00:25:19,762 --> 00:25:23,990
- Most guys are out by 50. 
- Yeah.

462
00:25:23,990 --> 00:25:27,668
- I tried taking a vacation once. 
- Yeah?

463
00:25:27,668 --> 00:25:30,722
Drove to Myrtle Beach, ten hours.

464
00:25:30,722 --> 00:25:34,070
Beautiful golf courses, shoreline...

465
00:25:34,070 --> 00:25:37,883
and I didn't know 
what to do with myself.

466
00:25:37,883 --> 00:25:40,107
So I drove back.

467
00:25:40,107 --> 00:25:43,214
I can't retire. 
I'd go nuts.

468
00:25:43,214 --> 00:25:46,749
I don't know how to not work.

469
00:25:46,749 --> 00:25:49,639
I used to think I only did this job  
because I was good at it.

470
00:25:49,639 --> 00:25:53,236
But I keep doing it.

471
00:25:53,608 --> 00:25:56,772
I think it's what we  
actually like doing, Will,

472
00:25:56,772 --> 00:26:00,172
crummy people and all.

473
00:26:00,776 --> 00:26:02,583
Come on in.

474
00:26:02,583 --> 00:26:04,202
I got to watch the phones.

475
00:26:04,202 --> 00:26:07,170
You can hear them from here.

476
00:26:21,212 --> 00:26:24,512
Happy birthday, Will.

477
00:26:38,630 --> 00:26:40,544
Thank you for seeing me, Johanna.

478
00:26:40,544 --> 00:26:43,484
Coming all the way from Philadelphia.

479
00:26:43,484 --> 00:26:47,456
- It must be important. 
- It is.

480
00:26:47,456 --> 00:26:51,494
It's about a murder in 1945.

481
00:26:51,494 --> 00:26:55,797
- Who was killed? 
- A reporter. Lorena Kinney.

482
00:26:55,797 --> 00:26:58,147
Lo Kinney was murdered?

483
00:26:58,147 --> 00:27:02,212
Pushed in front of a train. 
The same night you left Philly.

484
00:27:02,212 --> 00:27:05,652
- I never knew. 
- But you knew Lo?

485
00:27:05,652 --> 00:27:10,013
I met her... once.

486
00:27:11,014 --> 00:27:14,081
- I wish I never had. 
- Why is that?

487
00:27:14,081 --> 00:27:19,606
Because... 
What she told me...

488
00:27:19,606 --> 00:27:25,783
haunted me... 
the rest of my life.

489
00:27:31,226 --> 00:27:34,457
I'm writing a story about 
someone from your hometown.

490
00:27:34,457 --> 00:27:36,934
From Swalmen?? Who?

491
00:27:36,934 --> 00:27:39,002
Noah Pool.

492
00:27:39,403 --> 00:27:42,893
- Noah. 
- You know him?

493
00:27:42,893 --> 00:27:45,945
We lived on same street since childhood.

494
00:27:45,945 --> 00:27:47,495
Is that right?

495
00:27:47,495 --> 00:27:51,238
His sisters and I, we played  
every day. Noah, too.

496
00:27:51,238 --> 00:27:56,872
So strong.  
But also so gentle.

497
00:27:56,872 --> 00:28:00,869
Yes. He is very gentle.

498
00:28:00,869 --> 00:28:03,448
- Is?  
- I know him.

499
00:28:03,448 --> 00:28:05,667
- He lives here in Philadelphia. 
- That is impossible.

500
00:28:05,667 --> 00:28:07,931
He'll be so pleased to know someone  
from Swalmen is also here.

501
00:28:07,931 --> 00:28:10,584
Noah is dead.

502
00:28:11,185 --> 00:28:13,369
What?

503
00:28:13,369 --> 00:28:17,622
He was killed in Auschwitz.

504
00:28:18,562 --> 00:28:21,125
You must be mistaken.

505
00:28:21,125 --> 00:28:25,308
He survived longer than the others,  
painting portraits.

506
00:28:25,308 --> 00:28:29,407
But when there are no more to paint...

507
00:28:29,407 --> 00:28:33,188
I, uh... I have a photo of him.

508
00:28:34,205 --> 00:28:37,005
This is Noah Pool.

509
00:28:40,777 --> 00:28:43,146
No.

510
00:28:44,655 --> 00:28:47,622
Then who?

511
00:28:49,464 --> 00:28:54,344
- That is Anton. 
- Anton?

512
00:28:54,670 --> 00:28:58,261
A guard.

513
00:28:58,766 --> 00:29:01,925
Are you sure?

514
00:29:02,566 --> 00:29:06,294
He gave me this.

515
00:29:25,449 --> 00:29:28,678
I left Philadelphia that day.

516
00:29:28,678 --> 00:29:33,614
Knowing he was there, 
I've never been back.

517
00:29:33,614 --> 00:29:38,127
So Lo was in love with a Nazi.

518
00:29:44,059 --> 00:29:45,525
Sit down.

519
00:29:47,517 --> 00:29:49,744
So we're looking for your uncle.

520
00:29:49,744 --> 00:29:52,213
- Must be at his studio. 
- No.

521
00:29:52,213 --> 00:29:54,739
- He cleared out. 
- Where would he go?

522
00:29:54,739 --> 00:29:57,470
That's what I need to know.

523
00:30:00,807 --> 00:30:04,560
The man you thought 
was your Uncle Noah,

524
00:30:04,560 --> 00:30:08,088
- he's someone else. 
- What do you mean?

525
00:30:08,088 --> 00:30:10,064
His real name's Anton Bikker.

526
00:30:10,064 --> 00:30:12,936
And he collaborated 
with the Germans.

527
00:30:12,936 --> 00:30:14,799
What do you think 
you're saying to me?

528
00:30:14,799 --> 00:30:17,141
I know how you feel about him, 
and how he helped bring you up.

529
00:30:17,141 --> 00:30:21,705
- That's right! 
- But people can lie, David.

530
00:30:22,129 --> 00:30:23,777
Trick you. 
And be real good at it.

531
00:30:23,777 --> 00:30:26,332
- I've known him my whole life. 
- He's been lying that long.

532
00:30:26,332 --> 00:30:28,029
Now he's running,  
and we got to find him.

533
00:30:28,029 --> 00:30:30,321
It can't be true.

534
00:30:30,321 --> 00:30:32,981
Noah played with me, 
taught me things.

535
00:30:32,981 --> 00:30:35,864
Took me to the movies.

536
00:30:37,569 --> 00:30:45,424
The real Noah died in a camp 
where Anton was a guard.

537
00:30:46,982 --> 00:30:49,846
We, uh...

538
00:30:50,963 --> 00:30:56,277
We found a woman  
who knew them both.

539
00:30:56,545 --> 00:31:03,265
60 years later... 
maybe a mistake.

540
00:31:03,265 --> 00:31:06,205
Can't see making a mistake about that.

541
00:31:06,205 --> 00:31:08,838
Can you?

542
00:31:12,210 --> 00:31:15,217
Johanna Hoffman told Lo the truth.

543
00:31:15,217 --> 00:31:17,391
Johanna Hoffman?

544
00:31:17,391 --> 00:31:20,093
You know the name?

545
00:31:20,093 --> 00:31:23,559
From the last time I saw Lo.

546
00:31:29,313 --> 00:31:31,502
You were going to meet us in the park.

547
00:31:31,502 --> 00:31:34,153
Ah... Oh, my, you're absolutely right.

548
00:31:34,153 --> 00:31:37,310
Where's my head? 
I... I lost track of time...silly me.

549
00:31:37,310 --> 00:31:42,276
Uncle Noah said cotton candy 
is your favorite. / It is.

550
00:31:43,620 --> 00:31:45,729
Thank you.

551
00:31:49,351 --> 00:31:52,209
What are you working on 
that you forget us?

552
00:31:52,209 --> 00:31:54,607
- Ah. Just my column. 
- Ah.

553
00:31:54,607 --> 00:31:56,746
More questions about recipes?

554
00:31:56,746 --> 00:31:59,695
No. No, not today.

555
00:32:01,941 --> 00:32:04,736
Lo.

556
00:32:05,380 --> 00:32:07,753
What is wrong?

557
00:32:07,753 --> 00:32:10,071
This one's hard.

558
00:32:10,071 --> 00:32:12,625
Why? What is it about?

559
00:32:12,625 --> 00:32:15,632
A woman... 
who thought she was in love.

560
00:32:15,632 --> 00:32:18,151
But the man she fell for 
wasn't who she thought he was.

561
00:32:18,151 --> 00:32:20,905
If she loves him...

562
00:32:21,469 --> 00:32:24,993
maybe who he is is okay.

563
00:32:24,993 --> 00:32:29,131
No, this fella is smart 
and handsome and kind.

564
00:32:29,131 --> 00:32:31,375
And for a while, 
she thought he hung the moon.

565
00:32:31,375 --> 00:32:33,547
- Did he hurt her? 
- Not her.

566
00:32:33,547 --> 00:32:36,390
Then what is the problem?

567
00:32:36,390 --> 00:32:40,457
If there is love between two people,

568
00:32:40,457 --> 00:32:42,480
nothing else matters.

569
00:32:42,480 --> 00:32:44,969
The problem is things  
he's done in the past.

570
00:32:44,969 --> 00:32:47,692
How can she believe them

571
00:32:47,692 --> 00:32:53,439
if for her, he hangs the moon?

572
00:32:58,099 --> 00:33:00,641
Miss Kinney, you have that letter?

573
00:33:00,641 --> 00:33:03,603
Oh, yes, yes.

574
00:33:03,603 --> 00:33:05,495
Here.

575
00:33:08,452 --> 00:33:13,420
Going to a Miss Johanna Hoffman on pine?

576
00:33:17,510 --> 00:33:19,968
Yes.

577
00:33:28,546 --> 00:33:33,311
So Lo didn't receive that note,  
she wrote it to Johanna.

578
00:33:33,311 --> 00:33:34,986
Sent it the day she died.

579
00:33:34,986 --> 00:33:39,764
But Johanna had left Philly for good,  
so it went back to Lo.

580
00:33:39,764 --> 00:33:45,785
Did your, um... 
uncle see this letter?

581
00:33:47,808 --> 00:33:50,082
No.

582
00:33:50,844 --> 00:33:55,293
But I told him what is said.

583
00:33:57,140 --> 00:34:02,103
Anton stood by while 
your real uncle was killed,

584
00:34:02,103 --> 00:34:05,056
and when Lo Kinney found out 
about his lies,

585
00:34:05,056 --> 00:34:07,787
he killed her, too.

586
00:34:07,787 --> 00:34:12,069
I always wondered why he 
stopped talking about her.

587
00:34:12,069 --> 00:34:14,988
Where is he?

588
00:34:16,291 --> 00:34:21,625
Tell us, for Noah.

589
00:34:29,807 --> 00:34:31,307
Anton.

590
00:34:32,412 --> 00:34:34,554
Anton Bikker.

591
00:34:34,998 --> 00:34:37,709
Where you going, Anton?

592
00:34:38,209 --> 00:34:39,766
Why do you call me that?

593
00:34:39,766 --> 00:34:42,030
Where do you think 
you can run to now?

594
00:34:42,030 --> 00:34:43,454
My name is Noah Pool.

595
00:34:43,454 --> 00:34:45,095
Noah Pool is dead.

596
00:34:45,095 --> 00:34:48,066
Talk to David, my nephew. 
He'll tell you.

597
00:34:48,066 --> 00:34:49,478
We did talk to him.

598
00:34:49,478 --> 00:34:53,668
Told him how you took his uncle's name  
to hide what you did during the war.

599
00:34:53,668 --> 00:34:56,865
- Oh, he wouldn't believe that. 
- How do you think we found you?

600
00:34:56,865 --> 00:35:00,590
He was disgusted by you, 
just like Lo.

601
00:35:00,590 --> 00:35:05,515
- Lo saw who I was and loved me. 
- No.

602
00:35:05,515 --> 00:35:08,531
When she knew the truth, 
she gave up on you.

603
00:35:08,531 --> 00:35:13,165
- No, she was confused! 
- Heartbroken.

604
00:35:14,025 --> 00:35:16,139
But she was going to do the right thing.

605
00:35:16,139 --> 00:35:17,798
Expose you.

606
00:35:17,798 --> 00:35:21,944
"This will not stand."

607
00:35:22,755 --> 00:35:27,597
I am better than the worst thing I ever did.

608
00:35:27,597 --> 00:35:34,647
I have to be able to go on now, to live. I...

609
00:35:39,964 --> 00:35:43,085
That's asking too much.

610
00:35:43,412 --> 00:35:46,778
She knew me! 
She should have been able to understand.

611
00:35:46,778 --> 00:35:50,808
What you did, no one can understand.

612
00:35:53,052 --> 00:35:57,523
If she had let herself love me...

613
00:35:58,206 --> 00:36:02,605
it all would have been okay.

614
00:36:29,374 --> 00:36:34,325
You were expecting Johanna. 
Why?

615
00:36:34,783 --> 00:36:37,314
I wanted to show her a story I wrote.

616
00:36:37,314 --> 00:36:40,421
A story? 
A story about what?

617
00:36:40,421 --> 00:36:45,558
A Nazi... who pretended to be a Jew.

618
00:36:45,818 --> 00:36:48,324
Did you know that when the camps  
were finally liberated,

619
00:36:48,324 --> 00:36:52,644
soldiers pushed empty baby carriages  
out the front gate... five at a time?

620
00:36:52,644 --> 00:36:55,199
Why are you telling me this?

621
00:36:55,199 --> 00:36:58,382
People watching said it took 
an hour for them all to pass by.

622
00:36:58,382 --> 00:37:00,962
And you believe this woman 
more than you believe me?

623
00:37:00,962 --> 00:37:02,999
Tell me your name.

624
00:37:02,999 --> 00:37:05,868
Don't play games, Lo.

625
00:37:05,868 --> 00:37:08,868
Tell me your name.

626
00:37:10,551 --> 00:37:13,665
Johanna saw the photo,

627
00:37:13,665 --> 00:37:17,580
the one we took together in the park.  
How could you?

628
00:37:17,580 --> 00:37:19,922
I am not a monster.

629
00:37:19,922 --> 00:37:22,050
Did you kill Noah Pool or  
just watch him die?

630
00:37:22,050 --> 00:37:26,236
I watched him paint. 
Hour upon hour,

631
00:37:26,236 --> 00:37:28,314
just the two of us,

632
00:37:28,314 --> 00:37:32,453
talking about his family in America,

633
00:37:32,453 --> 00:37:35,482
about a nephew David...

634
00:37:35,482 --> 00:37:38,001
how he wanted to meet them on day,

635
00:37:38,001 --> 00:37:41,786
and poetry and music and art.

636
00:37:41,786 --> 00:37:45,169
And in those hours, I saw.

637
00:37:45,169 --> 00:37:48,081
Saw?

638
00:37:48,081 --> 00:37:51,338
He was a man.

639
00:37:51,338 --> 00:37:57,744
Better than I. 
Forgive me.

640
00:37:58,800 --> 00:38:01,536
- No one can forgive you. 
- You can.

641
00:38:01,536 --> 00:38:05,082
Because you loved me. 
With you, I was free.

642
00:38:05,082 --> 00:38:08,216
- You're wrong. 
- That day in the park, you understood

643
00:38:08,216 --> 00:38:09,795
No, I didn't. 
Now let me go.

644
00:38:09,795 --> 00:38:12,309
You know me! 
Better than anyone!

645
00:38:12,309 --> 00:38:15,040
Noah Pool is dead, and  
everything I know is a lie!

646
00:38:15,040 --> 00:38:18,250
How we feel about each other... 
that is not a lie!

647
00:38:18,250 --> 00:38:20,313
I love you! 
And I know you love me!

648
00:38:20,313 --> 00:38:25,418
No, Anton, no! 
I loved Noah.

